<HEAD>Anorexia, Bulimia Are Growing Problem for Men</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-EXP--Food Obsessed, b0954-b0955</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARY MacVEAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Despite a new focus on being healthy rather than
merely thin, anorexia and bulimia continue to haunt young women,
and the number of men who suffer from eating disorders appears to
be growing.
   The last decade was full of images of the dangers of eating
disorders, on television and in movies and women's magazines.
   An anorexic teen-ager was a character in the movie ``Down and
Out in <LOCATION>Beverly Hills</LOCATION>.'' <PERSON>Jane Fonda</PERSON> told the world she had suffered
from bulimia. <PERSON>Karen Carpenter</PERSON> lost her life to an eating disorder.
Even a ``<DATE>Saturday</DATE> Night Live'' skit included an anorexic cookbook.
   The diseases have not gone away, though experts say estimates at
the time that <PERCENT>30 percent</PERCENT> of college women suffered from them were
exaggerated. And new pressures have come to bear on those who are
susceptible.
   ``It's not good enough just to be thin, but one has to have
muscles in the right places, for a man or a woman. You get into the
fat content of your body, how much muscle tone,'' said <PERSON>Leonard S.
Levitz</PERSON>, clincal director of the <ORGANIZATION>Renfrew Center</ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION>Philadelphia</LOCATION>,
which in <DATE>1985</DATE> became the first residential facility for treatment
of eating disorders.
   So now there is ``exercise bulimia,'' in which sufferers turn to
extraordinary amounts of exercise rather than, or in addition to,
laxatives or vomiting.
   Anorexia is estimated to be two to four times as common <DATE>today</DATE> as
30 years ago. Bulimia also appears to be more common. The best
estimates seem to be that <PERCENT>1 percent</PERCENT> to <PERCENT>3 percent</PERCENT> of college women
are afflicted, <PERSON>Levitz</PERSON> said.
   Anorexia nervosa is characterized by self-starvation, an intense
fear of becoming fat and a feeling that one is fat, despite being
emaciated. Bulimia involves a pattern of binge eating followed by
purging by vomiting or with diruetics.
   Although anorexia was identified in <DATE>1873</DATE> by a <LOCATION>London</LOCATION> physician,
there is a centuries-long history of women controlling their
appetites, <PERSON>Joan Jacobs Brumberg</PERSON> wrote in her book ``Fasting
Girls.''
   In the <DATE>1300s</DATE>, <ORGANIZATION>St. Catherine of Siena</ORGANIZATION> was said to eat only a
handful of herbs a day. In the midieval period, fasting was central
to female holiness.
   Bulimia, however, is newer, becoming epidemic only in <DATE>1973</DATE> or
<DATE>1974</DATE>, when ``a lot of trends came together in terms of broad
societal issues, concern over body weight, role of women, people
being under tremendous pressure to be perfect, the breakdown of
family life,'' <PERSON>Levitz</PERSON> said.
   A victim ``feels powerless in the world, no sense of control of
her life, and a real fear that if her eating, like her emotions,
got out of control, who knows what would happen,'' <PERSON>Levitz</PERSON> said.
   Treatment generally is an intensive combination of therapy,
education and behavior modification.
   These generally are diseases of intelligent women, found in the
middle and upper classes of developed countries. The incidence
appears to be increasing in <LOCATION>Scandinavia</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Japan</LOCATION> and <LOCATION>Germany</LOCATION>.
   New research is showing that many of those who suffer from
eating disorders dieted as preteen-agers, were sexually abused, or
abuse drugs or alcohol, <PERSON>Levitz</PERSON> said. Also linked to the disease are
such issues as fear of growth into womanhood.
   At adolescence, girls come to think of the normal changes
occurring in their bodies as fatness and enter a war of wills to
control them. Boys, however, take pride in their growth.
   The overwhelming majority of people with eating disorders are
women, but experts say more and more men are afflicted,
particularly those involved in weight-conscious pursuits like
wrestling, dancing or modeling.
   Is there a way out?
   Said Levitz: ``Yes, I think there's a way. And I used to be more
hopeful about it happening. The main thing we have to do is change
people's perceptions of how you deal with different body weights.
How you look is a part of how you are as a person. And there are
many, many other things that are equally or more important.''
</TEXT>
