<HEAD>Increase Seen In Anorexia Nervosa Among Young</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A children's hospital says anorexia nervosa is up
among diet-crazed girls as young as 8 years old who are worried
about their weight because of social pressure.
   ``It's part of the general culture that we live in where
fitness, slimness, health is very much promoted and some of that
rubs off on young children,'' said <PERSON>Rachel Waugh</PERSON>, a specialist in
childhood eating disorders at the <ORGANIZATION>Great Ormond Street Hospital</ORGANIZATION> for
Sick Children.
   <PERSON>Ms. Waugh</PERSON> said <DATE>Wednesday</DATE> that most people with anorexia nervosa
are in their teens or early twenties, but that the hospital has
seen an increase in referrals of younger girls. She gave no figures
or percentages.
   Parents should be alert to large weight losses in their children
or extremely selective eating habits, she said in a radio interview
with the <ORGANIZATION>British Broadcasting Corp</ORGANIZATION>.
</TEXT>
