<DESCRIPT>  BEVERAGE; RELATION; FOOD; DISEASE; LIFESTYLE; MEDICAL; RESEARCH  </DESCRIPT>
<LEADPARA>  Consuming too much caffeine may worsen binge eating, vomiting or other
behaviors associated with eating disorders, researchers say.;    A study at
the University of Michigan has found that people who suffer from eating
disorders and consumed more than 750 milligrams of caffeine a day binged,
vomited and exercised more than people whose caffeine intake was moderate or
light.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Front  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  TOO MUCH COFFEE MAY WORSEN BINGES
CAFFEINE LINKED TO EATING DISORDERS  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>     Fasting and use of laxatives, diet pills, diuretics or enemas were also
higher among heavy caffeine users, said <PERSON>Dr. Dean D. Krahn</PERSON>, author of the
study.;    The study is published in the <DATE>March</DATE> issue of the journal Hospital
and <ORGANIZATION>Community Psychiatry.</ORGANIZATION>;    High caffeine intake was defined as the
equivalent of about eight cups of coffee, 15 cups of tea or 16 12-oz. cans of
soda a day, <PERSON>Krahn</PERSON> said.;    Moderate caffeine intake consisted of between
three and eight cups of coffee, five to 15 cups of tea or five to 16 12-oz.
cans of soda a day, he said.;    People who drank less than three cups of
coffee, five cups of tea or five 12-oz. cans of soda a day were considered low
caffeine users, he said.;    Eating disorders, such as anorexia nervosa and
bulimia, are psychological problems characterized by a preoccupation with
being thin.;    More than 5 million women suffer from eating disorders,
according to the <ORGANIZATION>National Institute of Mental Health</ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION>Bethesda</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Md</LOCATION>. People
who suffer from such disorders may fast, vomit or take medications to lose
weight.;    <PERSON>Kahn</PERSON> studied 171 women with eating disorders.;    Moderate or
heavy caffeine users binged more than those whose intake was low, <PERSON>Krahn</PERSON> said.;
   They also experienced more severe anxiety and depression than low caffeine
users.;    Heavy caffeine users were more likely than moderate and light users
to smoke cigarettes and drink alcohol, which may indicate a greater tendency
to abuse other chemicals, <PERSON>Krahn</PERSON> said.  </TEXT>
