<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   <PERSON>Michael Jackson</PERSON> whirled and twirled his way <DATE>Monday</DATE>
through a show billed in the Japanese press as a ``farewell
concert'' but made no mention of retiring.
   Jackson spoke to the audience only briefly during the two-hour
show, the ninth and final concert of his current stand in <LOCATION>Tokyo</LOCATION>,
saying: ``Domo arigato (thank you) to everyone in <LOCATION>Japan</LOCATION>'' and ``I
love you, <LOCATION>Japan</LOCATION>.''
   In <DATE>August</DATE>, <PERSON>Jackson</PERSON>'s manager, <PERSON>Frank Dileo</PERSON>, said the tour probably
would be <PERSON>Jackson</PERSON>'s last. He said <PERSON>Jackson</PERSON>, 30, would go on to ``do
movies and other things.''
   <LOCATION>Tokyo</LOCATION> was supposed to be the final stop on the 14-month,
four-continent tour. But three shows in <LOCATION>Los Angeles</LOCATION> that were
canceled last month because <PERSON>Jackson</PERSON> had throat problems have been
rescheduled for next month.
   After <PERSON>Dileo</PERSON>'s comments, newspapers dubbed the <LOCATION>Tokyo</LOCATION> appearances
<PERSON>Jackson</PERSON>'s ``farewell concerts'' and promoters sold T-shirts and hats
emblazoned with that slogan.
   The nine concerts _ 450,000 tickets in all in the 50,000-seat
<LOCATION>Tokyo</LOCATION> Dome _ were quick sellouts.
   ``It's going to be lonely without <PERSON>Michael</PERSON>. It's as though his
life is over,'' said <PERSON>Yuriko Wada</PERSON>, an office worker from Kyoto who
attended the concert.
</TEXT>
