<HEAD>Disorders Affect Nutritional Needs, Study Shows</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A study suggests the nutritional needs of
women with eating disorders differ from those of normal women.
   A study by <ORGANIZATION>Western Psychiatric Institute and Clinic</ORGANIZATION> found that
women recovering from bulimia needed only <PERCENT>73 percent</PERCENT> of the normal
intake of calories. Conversely, women recovering from anorexia
needed two-thirds more calories than normal.
   Bulimia is the disorder of gorging and purging. Anorexia is an
avoidance of food.
   The study of 23 recovering bulimic women who were trying to
maintain normal weight found that the women required only 10
calories per pound of body weight, or <PERCENT>73 percent</PERCENT> of the 13.8 daily
calories per pound that healthy women need.
   Separate studies involving 31 recovering anorexic women found
they needed 22.3 calories per pound of body weight to maintain
their normal weight.
   ``These findings have led to new treatment methods in our
program ... and they help us to understand the physiological
factors that complicate the psychological issues of eating
disorders,'' said <PERSON>Dr. Walter Kaye</PERSON>, director of the institute's
Center for <ORGANIZATION>Overcoming Problem Eating</ORGANIZATION>.
   The findings were published in a recent issue of the <ORGANIZATION>American
Journal of Nutrition</ORGANIZATION> and released to the public <DATE>Tuesday</DATE> in
conjunction with <ORGANIZATION>Easting Disorders Awareness Week</ORGANIZATION>.
   The studies were conducted during the last three years, <PERSON>Kaye</PERSON>
said.
</TEXT>
