<HL> Researchers Link Some Binge Eating To Hormone Levels </HL>
<SO> </SO>
<IN> PHA </IN>
<DATELINE> BOSTON (AP)  </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Some binge eaters produce unusually small amounts of a hormone that ordinarily signals people that they are full, according to a study. 

   The report suggests that a defect in production of this natural chemical may be an underlying cause of bulimia nervosa, an eating disorder in which people stuff themselves with food and then make themselves vomit. 

   Other studies have shown that anti-depression medicine is an effective way to curb binge eating, and the latest research shows that the drugs also seem to increase levels of the appetite hormone after a meal. 

   However, the researchers say further study will be necessary to see if correcting the apparent hormonal abnormality is important in controlling bulimia. 

   The study was conducted by Drs. 
<PERSON>Thomas D. Geracioti Jr.</PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION>National Institute of Mental Health</ORGANIZATION> and <PERSON>Rodger A. Liddle</PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION>University of California</ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION>San Francisco</LOCATION>. 
It was published in <DATE>Thursday</DATE>'s New England Journal of Medicine. 

   The study compared 14 women with bulimia with 10 healthy volunteers. 
It found that after a meal, the binge eaters produced unusually low levels of cholecystokinin, a hormone released from the intestines that produces satiety. 

   In an accompanying editorial, Drs. 
<PERSON>David B. Herzog</PERSON> and <PERSON>Paul M. Copeland</PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION>Massachusetts General Hospital</ORGANIZATION> cautioned that "it is premature to conclude" that low hormone levels make people susceptible to binge eating. 

   But they added, "Investigating bulimia nervosa from the perspective of defective satiety offers a promising avenue of research." 

   They noted that <PERCENT>1%</PERCENT> to <PERCENT>4%</PERCENT> of young adult American women and a much smaller number of men are believed to have the disorder. 

</TEXT>
