<HL>
   Letters to the Editor:
   Attitudes on Eating
   Can Make You Retch
</HL>
<DATE>
12/27/91
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A11
</SO>
<LP>
   Your story about Carol Lopacich's disinheritance from the
Baxter International Inc. fortune ("She Might Have Inherited
Millions, But for Her Mother," page one, Nov. 25) because of
her parent's disapproval of her size is a shocking and
dramatic example of the high price women often pay because of
how they look.
   I suffered from bulimia from ages 15 to 22, partly because
my swim coaches never missed an opportunity to comment on how
important it was to be "lean and mean." Now as the president
of a foundation that assists others with the same problem, I
get thousands of letters from women who say it took just one
disparaging comment from a parent, coach or other authority
figure for them to start binging, starving, vomiting,
compulsively exercising and abusing laxatives. Some say their
parents even have scales set up next to the refrigerator to
determine whether they "deserve" to eat or not.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The most common precursor to developing an eating disorder
is "going on a little diet," and bulimia and anorexia
together have the highest mortality rate of any psychiatric
illness. So that ought to be food for thought for anyone who
is tempted to comment on another person's weight.
   <ORGANIZATION>Caroline Adams Miller
   President
   Foundation for Education About Eating Disorders</ORGANIZATION>
   <LOCATION>Middletown</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Md</LOCATION>.
</TEXT>
