<LEADPARA>  THE BEAUTY MYTH: How Images of Beauty; Are Used Against Women  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Arts &amp; Books  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  THE PRICE OF BEAUTY
FIXATION ON LOOKS MEANS LOSS OF POWER  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  Books
Faludi, a Wall Street Journal reporter based in San Francisco, recently won
the Pulitzer Prize for explanatory journalism. She is the author of "Backlash:
The Undeclared War Against American Women," which will be published in October.  </MEMO>
<TEXT>  By <PERSON>Naomi Wolf; Morrow</PERSON>, 291 pp., <MONEY>$21.95</MONEY>;  WHY, in an era when women are
supposedly freer than ever before, do so many middle-class women chain
themselves to private beauty torture chambers, starving and purging their
bellies, scalding their faces with Retin-A "treatments" and acid peels, or
slicing their body parts with plastic surgery (now the fastest growing medical
specialty in the <LOCATION>United States</LOCATION>)?;    Pop psychologists, so-called women's
health experts and, of course, women's magazine writers have tackled this
question in recent years, most with less-than-; illuminating insights.
Typically, these authorities wind up pointing an accusing finger at women's
liberation itself. Women have applied the feminist tenets of control and
mastery to their own bodies, they charge, and with devastating results. An
anorexic, they say, is an autonomous woman gone haywire.;    The more
psychoanalytically inclined look to the family for answers. They blame that
whipping girl of long-standing: Mom. It must be the pressures to please a
never-satisfied maternal figure that have turned the overachieving daughter
against her own flesh.;    Still others charge that the baby boom ethic is
behind the epidemic in eating disorders and the mania for liposuction and
breast implants. The Me Generation woman wants it all, they sniff, thin hips
and big breasts. She is greedy and so she binges and purges, literally having
her cake and eating it, too.;     In "The Beauty Myth," <PERSON>Naomi Wolf</PERSON> rejects
these explanations, and their tendency to assign responsibility to the
individual woman in isolation, and opts for a refreshingly political and
social analysis. Women are increasingly obsessed with perfecting their bodies,
she argues, not because they are overly feminist or self-indulgent but because
they have been subjected to a feminist-fearing and anything-but-indulgent
culture that has raised the stakes in the beauty market to an unbearable high.
American culture demands that women attain an aesthetic standard that is
virtually inhuman, and it offers, as a means of reaching its impossible goal,
tools that are increasingly painful, destructive and even deadly.;     The new
ideal, or "beauty myth," <PERSON>Wolf</PERSON> says, has arisen as a way of keeping the newly
independent woman down. "For every feminist action there is an equal and
opposite beauty myth reaction," <PERSON>Wolf</PERSON> writes. "The fixation on 'beauty' of the
<DATE>1980s</DATE> was a direct consequence of, and a one-to-one check and balance upon,
the entry of women into powerful positions." It advises women, as she aptly
recasts the old saw: "You are now too rich. Therefore, you cannot be too
thin.";    <PERSON>Wolf</PERSON> puts forward a set of disturbing, some by now
all-too-familiar, statistics on the ravages of this modern beauty fixation:
the reports that as many as one in five college women are anorexic or bulimic;
the studies that show breast implants have blocked the detection of cancer and
so facilitated its spread; the findings that liquid fast diets have led to 60
deaths and that liposuction operations have caused at least 14. As <PERSON>Wolf</PERSON>
rightly points out, even more appalling than the toll of the beauty myth is
society's -- and journalism's -- willingness to turn a blind eye to it, to
trivialize its origins as "vanity" and to promote its ends as "liberation."
The press, in particular, so often seems more interested in pimping for the
beauty industry than exposing its unattractive effects.;     The analysis that
Wolf offers, presented properly, might have provided much-needed fodder in
women's battle for equal status and self-respect. But <PERSON>Wolf</PERSON>, in her zeal to
make her case, grossly overstates it. She equates anorexics with AIDS victims
and Holocaust survivors. She claims that women's preoccupation with beauty has
"functionally supplanted" religion and become "a new fundamentalism
transforming the secular West, repressive and doctrinaire as any <ORGANIZATION>Eastern</ORGANIZATION>
counterpart." She asserts -- with little evidence -- that a "professional
beauty qualification" (or "the PBQ," as she irritatingly calls it) has been
"widely institutionalized as a condition for women's hiring and promotion" and
even "surgical alteration has become a requirement for women's employment and
promotion.";    She asserts baldly: "Since <DATE>1971</DATE>, the law has recognized that a
standard of perfection against which a woman's body is to be judged may exist
in the workplace, and that if she falls short of it she may be fired." To
document this last claim, she plucks a few court rulings from the record and
conveniently ignores the many legal decisions that went the other way. She
invokes <ORGANIZATION>Hopkins vs. Price Waterhouse</ORGANIZATION>, in which a female accountant denied
partnership was told she should have worn daintier dresses and more makeup.
But <PERSON>Wolf</PERSON> fails to mention that the ruling against <PERSON>Hopkins</PERSON> was overturned on
appeal.;    <PERSON>Wolf</PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION>Yale</ORGANIZATION> graduate who is now earning a doctorate as a <ORGANIZATION>Rhodes
Scholar</ORGANIZATION>, charges that "male-dominated institutions" (or, even more vaguely,
"the powerful") have consciously hatched the beauty-myth plot just to check
feminist advances. It seems more likely that the beauty industry's captains
are driven, first and foremost, by the desire to make money off women; the
wish to halt women's independence is a secondary, and largely subconscious,
aspect of that capitalist intent.;    Her analysis would have been both more
penetrating and persuasive if she had dropped the conspiratorial accusations
and explored instead the ways in which beauty marketers act out of a complex
set of motives, rooted in economic ambition, cultural anxieties, fears and
fantasies about women that beauty's architects barely understand themselves.; 
  <PERSON>Wolf</PERSON>'s identification of the beauty myth as the "only" remaining social
battering ram against liberated women is less than convincing, too. What of
the anti-abortion movement, or the corporate invention of "fetal protection
policies" that keep women out of the workforce, or <PERSON>Madison Avenue</PERSON>'s promotion
of "the mommy track" and the "New Traditional Woman," or the <ORGANIZATION>Supreme Court</ORGANIZATION>'s
devastating rollbacks in anti-discrimination legal protections? Surely, more
than a mirror stands between women and authentic equality today.  </TEXT>
