<LEADPARA>  ABOVE the desk in Naomi Wolf's cramped Broadway apartment hangs an uplifting
note.;   "Thank you, Naomi Wolf," it begins, telling the author of "The Beauty
Myth" -- the national best seller about the evil done to women by rigid
standards of beauty -- that "I could not put the book down."  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Living  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  THE BEAUTY BASHER
INCONVENIENTLY PRETTY NAOMI WOLF IS NOW A FREQUENT
MASS MEDIA SPOKESMOUTH AGAINST SOCIETY'S PERVERSE
IMAGES OF FEMALE BEAUTY
LOOKS AREN'T EVERYTHING, SAYS NAOMI WOLF. THEY'RE
JUST THE STRONGEST WEAPONS SOCIETY HAS TO KEEP
WOMEN OUT OF POWER AND IN THEIR PLACE  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  Cover Story  </MEMO>
<TEXT>     It's the kind of neighborly note, from a fellow West Sider -- signed "<PERSON>Yoko
Ono</PERSON>" -- that balances the nasty letter-plus-pornography Wolf just received in
the mail.;   Above the tank in <LOCATION>Wolf</LOCATION>'s cramped <LOCATION>West Side</LOCATION> bathroom are such
common aids to good grooming as <ORGANIZATION>Nexus Polymeric Styling Gel</ORGANIZATION>, Lubriderm lotion
and <ORGANIZATION>Queen Helene Mint Julep Masque</ORGANIZATION>. Modest obstacles to <ORGANIZATION>Nature</ORGANIZATION>'s completely
having its way with her body.;   They're the kind of toiletries that balance
the media insinuation that Wolf -- who does occasionally wear makeup -- is an
anti-beauty fanatic.;   And let's not forget above the thighs. Just above the
thighs on <ORGANIZATION>Wolf</ORGANIZATION>'s decidedly uncramped figure hang a pair of flimsy see-through
orange harem pants, scarcely obscuring black panties, signaling the
interviewer (he steadfastly believes) that if he shows the slightest sign of
noticing, he's dead sexist meat.;   They're the kind of pants, on a sweltering
<LOCATION>Manhattan</LOCATION> <DATE>summer</DATE> <TIME>afternoon</TIME>, guaranteed to set one thinking about hidebound
assumptions.;   So how to describe Wolf? "Beautician" doesn't quite capture
her, even if she does like to go into the beauty parlance at a moment's
notice. "Aesthetician" doesn't catch her either, though, like <PERSON>Byron</PERSON>'s lovely,
she walks in beauty (not to mention those pants) and likes a fight.;   No,
this inconveniently pretty 28-year-old <ORGANIZATION>Rhodes Scholar</ORGANIZATION> and Yale-educated
populist, suddenly a frequent mass media spokesmouth ("20/20," "The Oprah
Winfrey Show") against society's perverse images of female beauty, has created
her own category.;   Call her the Beauty Marx.;   "I didn't write this book so
you can sit there having a 'good read,' " she says with a laugh -- or was that
a sneer? -- hunched on a couch in her functional digs near <ORGANIZATION>Lincoln Center</ORGANIZATION>. "I
wrote it to enact social change.";   Of course. And if <PERSON>Karl Marx</PERSON> were still
functioning, he'd agree that the first step toward changing the world these
days is to alter the best-seller list by getting on it. Wolf pulled that some
few months after her stint of indefatigable publicity and promotion began:
"The Beauty Myth" grabbed the bottom rung of the <ORGANIZATION>New York Times</ORGANIZATION> non-fiction
best-seller list.;   And scores of media encounters and debates with originals
from <PERSON>Betty Friedan</PERSON> to Screw publisher <PERSON>Al Goldstein</PERSON> haven't changed this Oxford
doctoral candidate's mind.;   "Yes, there's been a change in my thinking,"
<PERSON>Wolf</PERSON> says about her tour for the book, her mischievous smile suggesting a
surprise is coming. "The change is that what I had hypothesized I now believe
more strongly than ever. I'm more certain that I'm right.";   Her book's basic
idea, expressed in the opening chapter, is that "we are in the midst of a
violent backlash against feminism that uses images of female beauty as a
political weapon against women's advancement.";   In <PERSON>Wolf</PERSON>'s view, the beauty
myth is a "social reflex" necessary to control women who, released by feminism
from earlier mystiques of "motherhood, domesticity, chastity and passivity,"
threaten the values of the dominant culture. Sometimes consciously, but more
often not, male-dominated culture has bombarded us with innumerable images by
which the "gaunt youthful model" can supplant the "happy housewife as the
arbiter of successful womanhood.";   In doing so, it sentences contemporary
women, and not just those in "display" occupations such as models, to a "third
shift." On top of paid work and housework, the modern woman must take on
"beauty maintenance" in a probably unattainable quest to reach an unnatural
standard of beauty.;   The beauty trap;   As <PERSON>Wolf</PERSON> describes them, "the <MONEY>$33
billion-a-year</MONEY> diet industry, the <MONEY>$20 billion</MONEY> cosmetics industry, the <MONEY>$300
million</MONEY> cosmetic-surgery industry and the <MONEY>$7 billion</MONEY> pornography industry,"
play a powerful role in creating this "collective reactionary hallucination."
So do mass media, with advertising-dominated women's magazines the worst
offenders.;   One result is the enormous rise Wolf reports in anorexia and
bulimia. Wolf was anorexic as a 13-year-old in <LOCATION>San Francisco</LOCATION>, though she says
her catalyst for writing the book was "being an adult and having to struggle
to be taken seriously because I had long hair.";   In arguing for her thesis,
<PERSON>Wolf</PERSON> supplies plenty of bite-size facts, often rapidly strung together, but
usually supported by footnotes. Some "33,000 American women told researchers
that they would rather lose 10 to 15 pounds than achieve any other goal." The
average weight of fashion models recently "plummeted to <PERCENT>23 percent</PERCENT> below that
of ordinary women." Every year, 150,000 American women die of anorexia.;  
Along the way, she bluntly describes the ugly mutilations endured for the
beauty myth -- stomach-stapling, breast implants, jaw-wiring. She draws sharp
analogies between traditional religion and the diet and cosmetic gospels, and
urges women to permit one another greater freedom to reject the myth's
pressures.;   <PERSON>Wolf</PERSON>'s mix of fact and argument, called a "cultural hand
grenade" in <LOCATION>England</LOCATION>, has won kudos from many feminists. <PERSON>Germaine Greer</PERSON>
cheekily called "The Beauty Myth" "the most important feminist publication
since 'The Female Eunuch' " -- her own career-making study. Wolf, true to her
principles, grew so outraged after British reviewers "fetishized" her jacket
photo -- paying it excessive attention under what she terms the old "bimbo or
hag" criterion applied to feminists -- that she refused to OK a photo on the
American edition from <LOCATION>William Morrow.</LOCATION>;   On the other hand, no less than <PERSON>Betty
Friedan</PERSON>, author of "The Feminine Mystique," called the book an "obsolete
rehash," disparaging <PERSON>Wolf</PERSON> for portraying women as overly passive. Critics have
faulted <PERSON>Wolf</PERSON> for contending that dominant male institutions "intentionally
conspire" to oppress women with ideals of beauty. They've said she exaggerated
too much, extrapolated too much from her own experience, drew a tasteless link
between Holocaust victims and the anorexic, and allowed big sociological
explanations to blind her to the importance of individual choice and
responsibility.;   Dueling words;   <PERSON>Wolf</PERSON>, already planning a book on female
sexuality, welcomes the chance to rebut criticisms. After three years of
studying women's history at <LOCATION>Oxford</LOCATION>, and another three in <LOCATION>Edinburgh</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Wolf</LOCATION>
plainly relishes philosophical argument as much as any Oxbridge debater. She
responds smartly and cannily to questions about the book.;   <PERSON>Wolf</PERSON> points out
that anyone who accuses her of "conspiracy theory" is a sloppy reader, because
she states in the book that the Beauty Myth is "not a conspiracy theory" and
needn't be. She simply believes in systemic, sociological "invisible hand"
analyses, and repeatedly sidesteps the opportunity to blame anyone in
particular for the Beauty Myth, whether it be a <ORGANIZATION>Revlon</ORGANIZATION> executive, <ORGANIZATION>Ford</ORGANIZATION> model
or actress.;   "<PERSON>Jane Fonda</PERSON>," she cracks, "is not the issue.";   Similarly, she
points out that her analogy to Holocaust victims is narrowly drawn, a physical
rather than experiential comparison. To the charge of exaggeration, she
replies that she often earns the right, through sustained argument, to a claim
such as, "To be anorexic or bulimic is to be a political prisoner.";   Perhaps
most important, she pooh-poohs the idea that for <PERSON>Naomi Wolf</PERSON>, a thing of beauty
is a pain forever. She stresses that "seeing beautiful women isn't the
problem. It's seeing beautiful women in the absence of any other kind of
representation.";   "If Time magazine couldn't show <PERSON>Gorbachev</PERSON> because
Minoxidil was a major advertiser," she cheerily remarks, "if your only role
models were fashion models, you would be very vulnerable to conforming to what
the Nautilus man looks like.";   Ah, men. The sudden introduction of the
species leads one to ask whether her boyfriend, an editor at a <LOCATION>New York</LOCATION>
newspaper, can get away with telling her that he hates what she's wearing.
Wolf laughs, but notes, "Going out with me is a challenge. . . . I'm always
trying to be aware of gender patterns in the relationship.";   No, she doesn't
lack a sense of humor. But neither does she think she's required to have one
on the subject of her book. "Yes, I'm very angry," she says, "because I almost
died of the Beauty Myth." She finds it "astonishing" that people aren't more
angry that "their daughters are at risk from the same thing.";   "Women are
dying of understatement," she says. "I know an eating disorder is crippling.
Listen to the word we use, 'disorder.' It's such a tiny thing -- just
something slightly out of order.";   There's unquestionably a graduate-student
cockiness to <PERSON>Wolf</PERSON>'s take on the world. Every piece of data thrown up to her
somehow "confirms," or "proves," or "corroborates" her thesis.;   In the case
of tough-on-feminism scholar <PERSON>Camille Paglia</PERSON> ("A terrible moral cowardice") and
<PERSON>Madonna</PERSON>'s supposed power over her career ("A placebo for real power"), <PERSON>Wolf</PERSON>'s
tolerance proves only skin deep.;   "There's two things <ORGANIZATION>Madonna</ORGANIZATION> can't do,"
<PERSON>Wolf</PERSON> says coolly. "She can't age. And she can't take off her makeup."  </TEXT>
