<HEAD>Health Care: School Nurse</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Most people don't really know what the role of the school nurse
is, says a nursing educator, who believes finding out can be
helpful to students, parents and teachers alike.
   ``I think a lot of people don't have any idea what the role of
the school nurse is,'' says <PERSON>Ruth Young Seideman</PERSON>, a former school
nurse who now is an associated professor of nursing at the
<ORGANIZATION>University of Oklahoma Health Sciences Center</ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION>Oklahoma City</LOCATION>.
``It's not as obvious as that of a teacher.''
   School nurses, she says, don't spend their time waiting for a
chance to hand out a Band-Aid, but on health monitoring, counseling
and disseminating information.
   ``We do not distribute drugs except in rare cases with a
doctor's order,'' she says. ``So while we will do CPR
(cardio-pulmonary resuscitation) or distribute aspirin, actually
treating patients is the exception rather than the rule.''
   A major part of the job, she says, is to serve as a referral
source, ``a resource person, to put the parents and teachers in
touch with health care providers.''
   The problems of a school nurse vary with the ages of the
students and the environment of the school district, she says.
   In elementary schools, the most common duties are identifying
communicable diseases, screen for health problems and coping with
playground accidents.
   In the high school setting, there are more delicate situations
of pregnancy, sexually-transmitted diseases and birth control, says
<PERSON>Seideman</PERSON>.
   Dental problems are there in all ages, she says.
   A constant project is teaching good nutrition and many school
nurses go into the classroom to provide information that they hope
will be passed along to parents. ``Connected with that,'' says
<PERSON>Seideman</PERSON>, ``the older girls often get preoccupied with their
weight, and then you need to be alert to symptoms of eating
disorders like anorexia and bulimia.''
   Not everything is a ``crisis,'' however. ``There are always a
few math-generated headaches,'' she says, ``when they come down
with the daily headache just in time for fourth-period math.''
</TEXT>
