<MEMO>  See also related story on page 1D of this section.  </MEMO>
<TEXT>  of dyslexia; An <LOCATION>Arkansas</LOCATION> study of more than 500 males revealed that those born
in the <DATE>summer</DATE> -- particularly in <DATE>June</DATE> -- have a higher incidence of dyslexia
than those born in other months.;   The higher risk may be linked to women
contracting winter viruses during the middle of their pregnancies, according
to <PERSON>Richard Livingston</PERSON>, head of Child and Adolescent Psychiatry at the
<ORGANIZATION>University of Arkansas</ORGANIZATION>. Mid-pregnancy is an important time for fetal brain
development, so maternal illness at that time may lead to disorders such as
dyslexia.;   Dyslexia is a learning disability characterized by problems with
reading.;   <PERSON>Livingston</PERSON> says that of 585 males who attended the university's
<ORGANIZATION>Child Studies Center</ORGANIZATION>, 173 had dyslexia. Those born in <DATE>June</DATE> were 2.7 times as
likely to have it as males born in other months. Those born in <DATE>May</DATE> and <DATE>July</DATE>
were approximately twice as likely to be dyslexic than those born in other
months.;   <PERSON>Livingston</PERSON> says the study is important because "it suggests you
could decrease the incidence of dyslexia by reducing maternal exposure to the
flu." That could be accomplished with vaccines now recommended for the elderly
and those with immune deficiencies.;   In addition, earlier diagnosis and
intervention could be established for children at risk. Parents who think
their child might be at risk should watch for difficulties in language
development and such skills as the ability to draw shapes or put things in
sequential order. Such children should be evaluated by learning-disorder
experts.;   <PERSON>Livingston</PERSON> says females were not included in the study because
there were too few dyslexic females in the study population.;   The capable;
single parent; Single parents should view themselves as competent and resist
falling victim to prejudices and stereotypes against them, urges <PERSON>Pirooz
Sholevar</PERSON>, professor and director of the <ORGANIZATION>Division of Child</ORGANIZATION>, Adolescent and
Family Psychiatry at <ORGANIZATION>Jefferson Medical College</ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION>Philadelphia.</LOCATION>;   In that
way, single parents can help change society's view that a two-parent family
automatically is "functioning" and a one-parent family must be viewed as
"broken.";   But to function best, <PERSON>Sholevar</PERSON> adds, single parents need to
surround themselves with a support group that helps members solve problems
rather than simply commiserate. "The point is to recognize (that) there are
single-parent families that are operating well," <PERSON>Sholevar</PERSON> says. "Our view is
that the single-parent family is as likely to be functioning as not.";  
<PERSON>Sholevar</PERSON> says society has a negative opinion of single parenthood because of
the stigma of divorce and of unwed pregnancy. But he points to studies of
single-parent black families -- largely headed by women -- that for
generations have raised children successfully. He says the successful single
mothers are those who share some of their child-rearing burden with a support
network of their own mothers, sisters, ministers, friends or partners.;   But,
<PERSON>Sholevar</PERSON> adds, society must abandon negative stereotypes about single-parent
families in order to help them thrive.;   The great; weight debate; <PERSON>Ann
Childress</PERSON>, a fellow in Child and Adolescent Psychiatry at the <ORGANIZATION>Medical
University of South Carolina</ORGANIZATION>, added results of another study to those that
shows an alarming number of children as young as 9 years old -- particularly
girls -- are extremely concerned about appearance and have tried to lose
weight.;   In a recent study of 3,000 <LOCATION>South Carolina</LOCATION> students in grades 5
through 8, more than <PERCENT>40 percent</PERCENT> say they are fat and need to lose weight.
Almost one-third say they have dieted -- and the youngest participants were
only 9 years old.;   <PERSON>Childress</PERSON> says <PERCENT>4.8 percent</PERCENT> of the youngsters admit they
have induced themselves to vomit to lose weight; <PERCENT>2.5 percent</PERCENT> say they have
used diet pills; and <PERCENT>1.5 percent</PERCENT> say they have used diuretics or laxatives to
lose weight.;   The children often pick up dieting behavior from their
parents, the study shows.;   The long-term solution, <PERSON>Childress</PERSON> says, is to
foster a society in which people can be comfortable with themselves regardless
of appearance. In the short-run, she advocates educating youngsters about the
dangers of extreme methods for weight loss.;   "Children can die from
vomiting," <PERSON>Childress</PERSON> says. "Children need to be educated about eating
disorders.";   <ORGANIZATION>Childress</ORGANIZATION> urges parents who suspect their child has an eating
disorder to contact school or local health organizations for information or
referrals.  </TEXT>
