<LEADPARA>  Psychoanalyst R. Peery Grant calls it "an intriguing idea.";    Health
economist Deborah Chollet says it's "obviously a productivity issue."  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Business  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  A QUESTION TO SLEEP ON: DO NAPS SPUR PRODUCTIVITY?  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>     But employee services director <PERSON>Jim Connolly</PERSON> gravely observes that <ORGANIZATION>Atlanta
Gas Light Co.</ORGANIZATION>'s rate payers might take a dim view of the utility's employees
curling up for 40 winks after lunch.;    That's right, we're talking about
naps.;    Over the last few years, medical journals and the popular press have
suggested that people innately long for 40 winks in the middle of the day.;   
Former <LOCATION>New York</LOCATION> vascular surgeon <PERSON>Irv Dardick</PERSON> recently gave up a traditional
practice to track his notion that the human body seeks harmony. Its health
results from rhythmic cycles of exertion and rest.;    "Most people have
sedentary jobs and sit for long hours in unchanging indoor environments," <LOCATION>New
York</LOCATION> magazine noted in a recent article about <PERSON>Dardick</PERSON> and his theory on the
marriage of work, rest and health.;    "Naps are not possible, despite the
body's natural inclination to rest at midday. People tend to eat too much, too
often, particularly high-fat foods, which are not easily digested -- and which
reinforce a flat pattern of energy recovery without much expenditure," the
article said.;    <PERSON>Dardick</PERSON> puts his patients, who are or have been chronically
ill with grave muscular diseases and illnesses such as anorexia nervosa,
through designed agendas of running, hopping, skipping and rest.;    He
theorizes that chronic disease is linked to behavior -- starting even as
children are seated in a classroom until <TIME>3 p.m.</TIME> and afterward, before a TV
screen -- and that is consistent with views about human history.;    Humans
have been office dwellers for less than a century, so isn't that kind of work
schedule unnatural for most people?;    "Certainly," says <PERSON>Peter J. Brown</PERSON>,
chairman of <ORGANIZATION>Emory University</ORGANIZATION>'s anthropology department. "There's no reason we
should expect work patterns to go eight hours unlimited.;    "I can't say
there's something in our evolutionary heritage that (dictates) we should take
naps, but in our hunter-gatherer history," we spent a good deal of time
resting.;    Work was then, and perhaps should be now, intermittent.;   
"Huh?" snorts <PERSON>Irwin Lowenstein</PERSON>. The live-wire president of <ORGANIZATION>Rhodes Furniture
Co.</ORGANIZATION> barely knows the meaning of the word "rest." And however he esteems his
employees, he's got no intention of providing a darkened room with partitions
and cots where folks could go to nod off for 20 or 30 minutes after lunch.;   
"I have no urge to nap at <TIME>2 this afternoon</TIME>," <PERSON>Lowenstein</PERSON> announces,
emphatically. "It'd take me an hour to get back on track. I've been up since
<TIME>5:30 this morning</TIME>, and I'm on a roll.";    It's staying on that endless,
merciless "roll" that makes closing one's eyes for even a few minutes seem
wimpy -- especially to today's upwardly mobile professionals, whether they're
young or not.;    It's better to give people a little relief from
stress-producing situations, Grant says. He asks: "If offices have gyms, why
not quiet rooms? For some people, (midday) exercise might be the most
stress-reducing. For others, it might be the quiet room.";    What are the
chances that companies -- many of which now provide employees with ways to
exercise -- might also provide a place to rest?;    "I think there'd be a lot
of resistance," says <PERSON>Grant</PERSON>, "because of the Calvinistic ethic, the idea that
we're 'good by our works.' Especially in the company mind, when you're on the
job you're supposed to be producing. That 'time away' might ultimately make
people more productive would be a hard sell.";    <PERSON>Lowenstein</PERSON> offers this: "I
think it's like smoking was 30 years ago. It took a while to convince us that
smoking was bad for everybody, but now we have smoke-free offices, and it's
not socially or professionally acceptable to smoke.";    If over time enough
information came down about naps, he admitted, he might change his mind. But
for now? Alas. There's no way he's going to give folks an hour off for a nap.;
   <LOCATION>Atlanta</LOCATION> Gas Light's <PERSON>Connolly</PERSON>, who said he did give the matter considerable
thought, could not see napping as part of the corporate culture, either.  </TEXT>
