<HEAD>Early Diet Book Holds Up Thin Ideal</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-EXP--Food Obsessed, b0954-b0955</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   ``Diet and Health with a Key to the Calories,'' published in
<DATE>1918</DATE> and written by a physician, was the first best-selling diet
book in this country, according to <PERSON>Joan Jacobs Brumberg</PERSON>'s history
of anorexia.
   It's full of good humor, but makes it cleaeal
had already taken hold. The author, <PERSON>Lulu Hunt Peters</PERSON>, uses names
like ``<PERSON>Mrs. Sheesasite</PERSON>, whose husband bought her freight scales,''
<PERSON>Mrs. Tiny Weyaton</PERSON> and <PERSON>Mrs. Ima Gobbler</PERSON>.
   Some excerpts:
   - To her readers whor that a thin id want to gain weight, she says:
``I am not
particularly interested in you, anyway, for I cannot get your point
of view. How anyone can want to be anything but thin is beyond my
intelligence.''
   - ``Now fat individuals have always been considered a joke, but
you are a joke no longer. Instead of being looked on with friendly
toleranace and amusement, you are now viewed with distrust,
suspicion and even aversion! How dare you hoard fat when our nation
needs it?''
   - ``Yes, you eat too much, no matter how little it is, even if
it be only one bird seed daily, if you store it away as fat. . . .
(And between you and me, <PERSON>Mrs. Weyaton</PERSON>, just confidential like -
don't tell it - we know that the small appetite story is a Medicine.
   That's obviously good news for people who want to reduce fat
intake, and it also may pay off for weight-watchers, she said.
   The federally financed study focused on six men who spent 24
hours a day for 13 days in a laboratory, where researchers could
precisely measure what they ate. The men did not know the purpose
of the study, and they were kept busy with a variety of tasks.
   Each man ate a high-fat, 844-calorie lunch during one three-day
period, and a low-fat, 431-calorie lunch in another period. Both
lunches consisted of submarine sandwiches and salad. The men could
not distinguish between the two versions.
   Beginning one hour after lunch, the men could choose from a
variety of foods to eat. Analysis showed that if they had eaten the
low-calorie lunch, they later made up the difference in calories,
mostly at dinnertime.
   But no such compensation occurred for fat, Rolls said. That
suggests fat substitutes ``certainly are going to be an aid to help
people to try to reduce fats in foods,'' she said.
   Hopkins researcher <PERSON>Richard Foltin</PERSON>, lead author of the study,
cautioned that the men were not free to eat whatever they wanted
for lunch. So the evidence is only suggestive that in everyday
life, low-fat food would reduce total fat intake, he said.
   <PERSON>Adam Drewnowski</PERSON>, director of the human nutrition program at the
<ORGANIZATION>University of Michigan's School of Public Health</ORGANIZATION>, called the study
valuable.
   He also said nobody knows what happens to overall fat intake
when people know they are eating low-fat products.
   Rolls said she doubts those people make up for missing fat. ``I
don't think people think in terms of `I want to eat fat,' '' she
said.
   Although the study found no difference in calorie intake, the
reduction in calories from fat may still be good news for those
trying to lose weight.
   Recent research suggests calories from fat are more fattening
than those from carbohydrates. That is because the body uses less
energy to convert fat calories to body fat than it uses to convert
carbohydrate calories, Rolls said.
   In theory, then, cutting back on fat may help in losing weight
beyond just the effect on reducing calorie intake, she said.
   Fat substitutes hit the headlines in <DATE>February</DATE> when the <ORGANIZATION>Food and
Drug Administration</ORGANIZATION> approved a substitute called Simplesse for use
in frozen desserts. Simplesse is made by <ORGANIZATION>Nutrasweet Co</ORGANIZATION>.
   <ORGANIZATION>Kraft General Foods Inc.</ORGANIZATION> is also seeking <ORGANIZATION>FDA</ORGANIZATION> approval for a fat
substitute to be used in frozen desserts.
   Another proposed substitute, olestra, could be used in cooking.
Olestra is not absorbed by the body, so it would not contribute any
fat or calories, says its developer, <ORGANIZATION>Procter &amp; Gamble Co</ORGANIZATION>.
   The company proposes that olestra replace some fat in oil and
shortening used in the home and in commercial frying.
   <ORGANIZATION>Frito-Lay Inc.</ORGANIZATION> is studying an experimental fat substitute,
dialkyl dihexadecymalonate, which it says cuts fat by <PERCENT>60 percent</PERCENT>
when blended with oil for frying tortilla and potato chips.
</TEXT>
