<HL>
   LEISURE &amp; ARTS -- Film:
   Bruce Willis as a Burglar; Madonna as Herself
   ----
   By Julie Salamon
</HL>
<DATE>
05/23/91
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A12
</SO>
<LP>
   During the promotional blitz for "Hudson Hawk," his latest
movie, the actor Bruce Willis repeatedly complained bitterly
and often that journalists keep harping on the picture's
cost. He has said that this obsession with money (the
agreed-upon rumor puts "Hawk's" budget at $75 million) "is
180 degrees away from the entertainment value of the movie
itself."
   Mr. Willis is correct. If "Hudson Hawk" were a wonderful
picture, or even a modestly entertaining one, no one -- apart
from its investors -- would care how much it cost. But the
money issue is difficult to ignore in this case. An eccentric
comedy lies somewhere in "Hudson Hawk," but, like the fine
cheekbones of a 500-pound person, it is almost entirely
obscured by bloat.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The movie is about a cat burglar (<PERSON>Mr. Willis</PERSON>), recently
released from jail and ready to start a new life -- without
crime. He and his partner and best friend (<PERSON>Danny Aiello</PERSON>) are
forced back into thievery by mobsters. These wiseguys are in
cahoots with Big Business and the <ORGANIZATION>Central Intelligence
Agency</ORGANIZATION>. In order not to miss a single movie cliche, the film
makers drag in the <ORGANIZATION>Vatican</ORGANIZATION> as well. The story moves from <LOCATION>New
York</LOCATION> to <LOCATION>Italy</LOCATION>, as everyone chases after <PERSON>Leonardo da Vinci</PERSON>'s
long-lost tools for changing lead into gold.
   The picture bears all the trappings of an enterprise
conceived and executed with too many hands, too little
thinking (simply invoking the name of Leonardo isn't enough).
The director, <PERSON>Michael Lehmann</PERSON>, and one of the screenwriters,
<PERSON>Daniel Waters</PERSON>, made their mark with "Heathers," a subversive
little comedy about teen-age suicide. Their hands are most
evident in the movie's "wacky" segments -- especially the
histrionics of <PERSON>Darwin</PERSON> and <PERSON>Minerva Mayflower</PERSON>, the scheming
capitalist couple who amuse themselves with sadomasochistic
sex and planning their bear play in the gold market. These
caricatures, played by <PERSON>Sandra Bernhard</PERSON> and <PERSON>Richard E. Grant</PERSON>,
seem like outtakes from a <ORGANIZATION>Monty Python</ORGANIZATION> movie -- or a <PERSON>Michael
Lehmann</PERSON> movie.
   But the film makers apparently were trying to pay homage
to stylish capers such as "To Catch a Thief," or the more
recent "Dirty Rotten Scoundrels," pictures in which witty
characters pull off their sleights of hand with great
panache. "Hudson Hawk" also wants to be an action picture,
and a dark comedy, and an international extravaganza. In
other words, it wants to be everything, and consequently it
isn't much of anything. Not one scene seems to lead logically
to the next, and the inconsistency of plot is matched by
inconsistency of tone. Even the music changes radically from
scene to scene.
   The only thing that never changes is <PERSON>Mr. Willis</PERSON>. He
maintains his earnest look of puzzlement no matter what seems
to be going on around him. It is an appealing look, and
worked well for him in the "Die Hard" pictures (which, like
"Hudson Hawk," were produced by <PERSON>Joel Silver</PERSON>). It might have
worked for him here if he were given better things to say and
do.
   But the film's jokes are lame, weak references to
existential factoids. They have no reason for being except
that they are. The mobsters are called the <ORGANIZATION>Mario Brothers</ORGANIZATION>;
presumably this refers to the <ORGANIZATION>Nintendo</ORGANIZATION> video game characters,
since someone mentions <ORGANIZATION>Nintendo</ORGANIZATION> -- once. There's a quip about
<PERSON>Karen Carpenter</PERSON>, the singer who died of anorexia nervosa.
There are many crotch jokes.
   The dialogue is never clever. Talking about the <PERSON>Willis</PERSON>
character's fondness for cappuccino, his friend says, "You've
still got a thing for these masculine European coffees." When
the woman he's attracted to asks him how long he's been in
prison, <PERSON>Mr. Willis</PERSON> says, "Let's say I never saw `E.T.'"
   Despite all its failures of wit, sense and pace, the film
does most effectively flaunt the millions spent on it. The
inane action takes place in splendiferous settings. <PERSON>Mr.
Willis</PERSON> may not want his audiences to think about how much
those settings cost, but I think he's making a mistake. The
picture's "entertainment value" can only be enhanced by the
realization that the movie's financiers are probably
suffering much more than the audience.
   ---
   "Truth or Dare," the "behind-the-scenes" (but entirely
authorized) documentary about <PERSON>Madonna</PERSON>, has quickly become the
most popular film ever distributed by <ORGANIZATION>Miramax Films</ORGANIZATION>, the
daring company that released "sex, lies, and videotape" and
"The Grifters."
   I don't have access to <ORGANIZATION>MTV</ORGANIZATION>, so my familiarity with <ORGANIZATION>Madonna</ORGANIZATION>
has pretty much been limited to radio and the multitude of
articles I've read about her. Friends of mine have very
strong opinions about her. One identifies with her
completely, and thinks she's a model for women everywhere
(strong, self-sufficient). Another thinks <ORGANIZATION>Madonna</ORGANIZATION> represents
the final decline of Western Civilization (sexual depravity,
money lust). After seeing "Truth or Dare," I think everything
everyone says about <ORGANIZATION>Madonna</ORGANIZATION> is true. She's great, she's
disgusting, she's profane, she's entertaining. She is what
she is and she doesn't hide any of it from the camera she let
follow her around -- even when she thinks she's hiding some
of it. The film is calculating, vulgar and too long -- as a
movie about a megolomaniac should be. Like Madonna herself,
this documentary is a powerfully shrewd piece of packaging,
and entertaining. You won't wonder for a minute how much it
cost.
   ---
   VIDEO TIP: After watching <ORGANIZATION>Madonna</ORGANIZATION> and <PERSON>Bruce Willis</PERSON> I had
an urge to watch "A Face in the Crowd" again. <PERSON>Andy Griffith</PERSON>
stars in this biting <PERSON>Elia Kazan</PERSON> picture about a nobody picked
up by a television executive and turned into a superstar.
</TEXT>
