<HEAD>U-Haul Plan Would Cost Workers with Unhealthy Lifestyles</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PHOENIX (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U-Haul International has a message for its
smokers and couch potatoes: Start leading a healthier lifestyle or
get lighter in the wallet.
   Starting <DATE>April 1</DATE>, the company will begin docking the pay of the
obese, the anorexic and the nicotine-needy by <MONEY>$5</MONEY> per paycheck _ up
to <MONEY>$130</MONEY> per year.
   Employees who quit smoking or get their weight under control
within two years will get refunds.
   The idea is not to harass employees who fall into those
categories but to save some of the company's <MONEY>$17 million-a-year</MONEY>
outlay for medical insurance and medical costs, executive vice
president <PERSON>Harry DeShong</PERSON> said.
   ``What we are trying to do is encourage people to maintain a
state of wellness. I suspect it's going to have a profound impact
on the organization,'' <PERSON>DeShong</PERSON> said.
   Two attorneys who specialize in labor relations said the idea
made them sick.
   ``It's ridiculous, grotesque,'' said <PERSON>Stanley Lubin</PERSON>. ``You don't
dock people for part of their pay that way. Pay is an agreed amount
of money given for an agreed amount of work. The company well may
be violating its employer-employee agreement if it docks people's
pay.''
   Lawyer <PERSON>Charles Santaguida</PERSON> said the policy was too simplistic.
   ``Many persons with weight problems, such as those linked to
diabetes, for example, are physically disabled,'' <PERSON>Santaguida</PERSON> said.
``And addiction to nicotine is considered to be a mental disability
under federal statutes, which prohibit discrimination on the basis
of either physical or mental disability.''
   Santaguida predicted the company would have to change the policy.
   <PERSON>DeShong</PERSON> said <PERSON>Santaguida</PERSON> was representing a client against U-Haul
in another labor matter.
   ``What's he going to do _ say something good about us?'' he said.
   <PERSON>DeShong</PERSON> said the plan was introduced company-wide through an
in-house newsletter last week and had met almost no opposition.
There is no organized effort to oppose implementation, he said.
   ``All of our employees are stockholders in the organization, and
the (medical) costs are such that we all suffer. Our
medical-benefits package affects 13,000 of us, and yet fewer than
150 employees comprise <PERCENT>80 percent</PERCENT> of what we spend in medical
claims,'' <PERSON>DeShong</PERSON> said.
   ``Those people, and all of us, need to be more
health-conscious,'' he said. ``We're not trying to decrease the
amount of coverage. We're trying to maintain the coverage we have.
   U-Haul Chairman <PERSON>Edward J.</PERSON> ``Joe'' <PERSON>Shoen</PERSON> was overweight and
recently lost 23 pounds to fall within the guidelines, and <PERSON>DeShong</PERSON>
said he was familiar with anorexia because of the struggle of a
member of his immediate family.
   U-Haul has no policy against hiring the obese, anorexic and
smokers, but <PERSON>DeShong</PERSON> said the company had been testing for drug use
by work applicants in <LOCATION>Arizona</LOCATION>, where it employes 2,300, for about a
year.
   About <PERCENT>7 percent</PERCENT> of the applicants either fail the urinalysis or
don't show up for the test.
   Alcohol abusers aren't included in the policy because of the
difficulty in monitoring borderline cases, but the company does
recognize alcoholism as a health threat and has programs in place
to help its workers break the addiction, <PERSON>DeShong</PERSON> said.
</TEXT>
