<LEADPARA>  DEAR ANN -- Two years ago, I found myself in the emergency room of a local
hospital. I had just swallowed a bottle of my mother's sleeping pills. I was
very much in love with a woman who repeatedly told me I was special -- one in
a million, etc. Unfortunately, she was married.;    I was a 20-year-old
college student when we met at work. She was a 27-year-old co-worker and
separated from her husband. We spent the summer together and it was very nice.
When she told me she and her husband were reconciling, I was hurt, but in the
back of my mind I had always known this would happen. What I didn't expect was
that she wouldn't want to break up. She really wanted both of us.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Living  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  THERE'S NOTHING THERE IF SEX IS ALL YOU SHARE  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>     I didn't know what to think or what to feel and I didn't have the strength
to tell her no. Now that I look back, our relationship was quite strange. This
woman would come to my apartment, have sex with me and leave. I could almost
set my watch by her words, "Oh, look at the time! I must go!";    I told her
several times that what we were doing was wrong and that I wanted to get on
with my life. She'd agree, then call me a couple of days later and whisper, "I
miss you. I can't live without you." It sure was flattering. But the mixture
of guilt, dependence, frustration and confusion made me crazy. Death seemed
like the only thing that could stop the pain.;    How can I keep this from
happening again?;    -- <LOCATION>M.P.</LOCATION> in <LOCATION>Washington</LOCATION>;    DEAR <LOCATION>WASHINGTON</LOCATION> -- If you
haven't already gone for counseling, I recommend it. In the future, find a
woman with whom you can share something besides a mattress. And your chances
would be better if you selected someone closer to your own age, with no
estranged husband in the background. I think you get the picture. P.S.: No
woman is worth swallowing a bottle of pills over. Good luck.;    DEAR ANN -- I
am an anorexic, bulimic, compulsive overeater who has spent too many years
binging, purging, starving, dieting and over-exercising. I want to tell you
and your readers how I got out of that prison. It was Overeaters Anonymous.;  
 I have been eating moderate meals for over five years, maintaining a healthy
weight and learning to enjoy myself. Best of all, I have discovered that I am
a worthwhile person.;    My life didn't miraculously turn perfect. My car
still breaks down, I still have to change the cat's litter box, and I still
feel lonely and frightened at times. But I no longer feel worthless, stupid
and hopeless.;    I'll be looking for my letter in the paper. Don't let me
down.;    -- Your Friend in <LOCATION>Durham</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>N.C.</LOCATION>;    DEAR <LOCATION>DURHAM</LOCATION> -- Here it is, and
it's a good one, too. I know of the great success many people have had with
Overeaters Anonymous and I recommend that group. Anyone who is interested
should send a long, self-addressed, stamped envelope to Overeaters Anonymous,
<PERSON>4025 Spencer St.</PERSON>, Suite 203, <LOCATION>Torrance</LOCATION> 90503.  </TEXT>
