<HL>
   Health:
   Slashes in Mental-Health Benefits Start
   To Hurt Patients, Medical Officials Say
   ----
   By Glenn Ruffenach
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
03/19/91
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B1
</SO>
<IN>
HEALTH CARE PROVIDERS, MEDICINE, DENTISTRY (HEA)
INSURANCE (INS)
</IN>
<LP>
   A backlash against the soaring cost of psychiatric care
may be backfiring.
   In the never-ending search for ways to slow the growth of
medical bills, many companies in the past two years have
seized upon mental-health benefits. Staggered by annual cost
increases of as much as 50% and frustrated by illnesses, like
depression, in which "cures" can be elusive, many employers
have taken a cleaver to coverage for psychotherapy,
substance-abuse programs and similar services.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   But the cutbacks, according to the medical community, are
beginning to hurt patients and their families. In the
extreme, say some psychiatrists, individuals who are suicidal
are being pushed out of hospitals long before such tendencies
can be reversed. More commonly, people who need counseling
for stress are finding that reimbursements for office visits
have been curtailed. Often the victims of the cuts are
children. Even those with chronic disorders are sometimes
booted from one treatment program to the next -- or bounced
from the medical system entirely.
   And the worst may lie ahead. Health professionals warn
that mental-health disorders that go untreated may develop
into medical problems, like ulcers or heart disease, and come
back to haunt corporate budget cutters in the form of even
larger bills.
   "It's a disaster," says <PERSON>Jonathan Slavin</PERSON>, director of the
counseling center at <ORGANIZATION>Tufts University</ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION>Medford</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Mass.</LOCATION>, who
notes that some students with severe depression or eating
disorders now find little help in their parents' insurance
plans. Sue <PERSON>Smith</PERSON>, director of <ORGANIZATION>Georgia Parents Support
Network</ORGANIZATION>, a nonprofit group that helps families with
emotionally disturbed children, says 30 days of lifetime
hospital care is all that many employers now pay for.
"Sometimes, you can't even get a good assessment in 30 days,"
she says.
   Medical providers, of course, aren't entirely selfless in
their concerns. Reduced benefits have meant reduced income
for many of them. Employers, meanwhile, argue that overly
aggressive physicians and hospitals have taken advantage of
mental-health plans, making some restrictions essential. Some
private psychiatric hospitals, for instance, coax individuals
into <MONEY>$600-a-day</MONEY> beds by quietly waiving <PERCENT>20%</PERCENT> co-payments from
patients, says <PERSON>Richard B. Spitznass</PERSON>, vice president for
compensation and benefits at <ORGANIZATION>Georgia-Pacific Corp.</ORGANIZATION> in
<LOCATION>Atlanta</LOCATION>.
   Once the patient is ensconced, "There's no financial
incentive {for the doctor or hospital} to move him into
lower-cost outpatient care," <PERSON>Mr. Spitznass</PERSON> says. "It's an
insidious problem."
   Still, interviews with state health officials, educators
and patients indicate that some employers have had a
knee-jerk reaction to such abuse, slashing benefits across
the board. As a result, they say, patients whose insurance
dollars are quickly exhausted are either being dumped into
state mental-health programs, which are often understaffed
and underfunded, or are simply going without care.
   In <LOCATION>Georgia</LOCATION>, for instance, only 18,000 of some 90,000
children who are severely emotionally disturbed will receive
help this year from community programs, says <PERSON>Ruth Coody</PERSON>,
director of child and adolescent services in the state's
<ORGANIZATION>Department of Human Resources</ORGANIZATION>. "We're just barely touching
the tip of the iceberg."
   Employers in the <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> now spend an estimated <MONEY>$17 billion</MONEY>
to <MONEY>$20 billion</MONEY> a year on mental-health services, and the
limitations on those benefits have affected both outpatient
and in-patient care. A survey last year by <ORGANIZATION>A. Foster Higgins
&amp; Co.</ORGANIZATION>, benefits consultants in <LOCATION>New York</LOCATION>, found that
three-fourths of companies now limit -- to about <MONEY>$2,000</MONEY> --
the annual payout for office visits. More than a third
require employees to pay a bigger share -- in some cases <PERCENT>50%</PERCENT>
-- of hospital bills for so-called behavioral care than for
other medical problems.
   In particular, companies have sharply reduced the lifetime
benefit for hospital care. Almost half of surveyed employers
have "capped" their payout at less than <MONEY>$50,000</MONEY>, and about
one-fifth now pay <MONEY>$20,000</MONEY> or less -- figures that represent a
fraction of the cost to treat serious disorders.
   <PERSON>Manuel Ellcorie</PERSON>, a 47-year-old management consultant in
<LOCATION>Atlanta</LOCATION>, says his insurance plan was providing sufficient
coverage for his son's lengthy hospital treatment, including
one 14-month stay that cost about <MONEY>$200,000</MONEY>. But in <DATE>1987</DATE>, the
lifetime benefit was capped at <MONEY>$25,000</MONEY>. Since then, <PERSON>Mr.
Ellcorie</PERSON> and his wife have gone through <MONEY>$50,000</MONEY> in savings
and have had to take out a <MONEY>$60,000</MONEY> home-equity loan to help
pay for their son's care.
   The <MONEY>$25,000</MONEY> cap, he says, is a "drop in the bucket -- it's
nothing if a child needs residential treatment." A struggle
to obtain help from state officials has, of late, provided
relief, <PERSON>Mr. Ellcorie</PERSON> says. But most families that turn to the
public sector find "no beds and no money," he says. "They're
left with few, if any, alternatives."
   Even when benefits provide for adequate care, families and
physicians say, insurers are pushing hard to suspend
treatment at the first hint of recovery. <PERSON>Linda Silber</PERSON>, a
psychologist in <LOCATION>Raleigh</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>N.C.</LOCATION>, says she recently hospitalized
a 13-year-old girl who was severely anorexic. The child's
weight had dropped to 72 pounds from 115 pounds in two
months, and -- in the hours before she was admitted for
treatment -- she had passed out three times. "She was
starving," <PERSON>Dr. Silber</PERSON> says.
   After almost three weeks of care, the girl's weight
stabilized temporarily at <MONEY>85 pounds</MONEY> -- at which point her
insurance company demanded that she be discharged from the
hospital.
   The problem, says <PERSON>Dr. Silber</PERSON>, was that treatment of the
underlying psychological problems had barely begun. "We had
to get her weight and nutrition up first," she says, "but she
still needed help." An appeal to the insurer finally earned
the child a two-week reprieve, but <PERSON>Dr. Silber</PERSON> expects the
struggle over the girl's care to continue. "These are the
kinds of battles we have to fight all the time," she says.
   A few companies are beginning to take what some physicians
and patients consider a more enlightened approach to
controlling mental-health costs. Among the most popular is
"carving out" the benefits from the rest of a company's
medical plan and having them administered by a company that
specializes in psychiatric care. After watching its
mental-health costs rise about <PERCENT>30%</PERCENT> annually in the late
<DATE>1980s</DATE>, <ORGANIZATION>Harris Corp.</ORGANIZATION>, a <LOCATION>Melbourne</LOCATION>, Fla.-based electronics
concern, hired <ORGANIZATION>American PsychManagement</ORGANIZATION>, a unit of closely
held <ORGANIZATION>Value Health Inc.</ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION>Avon</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Conn.</LOCATION>, to help run its program.
   Under the plan, <ORGANIZATION>American PsychManagement</ORGANIZATION> provides a
network of therapists for <PERSON>Harris</PERSON> and monitors all psychiatric
hospital care. "We wanted to control costs without simply
cutting benefits," says <PERSON>Ron Wyse</PERSON>, director of compensation
and benefits at <LOCATION>Harris</LOCATION>, which has kept its own lifetime
maximum for hospital and outpatient care at <MONEY>$100,000</MONEY>.
Moreover, the company had discovered that most of its cost
increases were coming from a single source -- in-patient
treatment of employees' children -- and that there was no
need to make wholesale reductions in mental-health benefits.
   Indeed, a recent study by the <ORGANIZATION>American Psychiatric
Association</ORGANIZATION> indicates that companies' horror stories about
the cost of treating mental illness may be exaggerated. The
study found that the overall cost of psychiatric care rose
about <PERCENT>13%</PERCENT> between <DATE>1986</DATE> and <DATE>1988</DATE> -- on a par with other
medical expenditures. But the study also shows that the cost
of treating children and adolescents jumped almost <PERCENT>70%</PERCENT>.
   "Simply putting in limitations may be shortsighted," says
<PERSON>John Erb</PERSON>, a managing director at <ORGANIZATION>Foster Higgins</ORGANIZATION>. But some
companies, he adds, don't want to take the time -- or don't
have the time -- for a more measured approach. "It's cheap,"
he says, "it's easy, you don't have to hire a consultant, and
the effect is immediate."
